e <i>Írabýr</i> ‘settlement of the Irish’. Compare   Ireton  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Ireton","meanings":["English: most probably a habitational name from Kirk Ireton (Derbyshire) or perhaps from Ireton Farm in Weston Underwood (Derbyshire), both named in Anglo-Scandinavian as <i>Íratūn</i> ‘settlement of the Irish’ or more likely ‘settlement of the Irishman’. The reference may be either to a Scandinavian Viking who had been in Ireland or to an Irishman who came to England with the Vikings. Occasionally the name may also derive from either of two places called Irton in North Yorkshire, of which Irton in Seamer parish is a more likely source than the lost Irton in Coxwold. Both the North Yorkshire places have the same etymologies as those above."]},{"name":"Erby","meanings":["English: variant of   Irby  . This form of the surname is now rare in Britain."]}]},{"name":"Christiana","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Medieval learned feminine form of   Christian .  As a recent revival it represents an elaborated form of   Christina .  It is also sometimes spelled  <b>Christianna</b> , under the influence of the name   Anna ."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705188,"age":6,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705189,"age":41,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":1},{"id":1705190,"age":72,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semi